<span class="subtitle">Definition in markup</span>

<p class="description">
    Attributes for configuring bootnode must be set on a top-level or containing element of your application interface. There are 3 parameters to set
</p>
<p class="description">
    <b>class="bootnode"</b> : adding 'bootnode' to the element class permits Tetra to find which element is reactive to bootnode actions.
</p>
<p class="description">
    <b>data-event="click"</b> : the event that will trigger the download of the associated dependency. This attribute supports the click, mouseover and focus event type.
</p>
<p class="description">
    <b>data-view="appName/viewName"</b> : the path (scope/name) to the view of the associated dependency. This view, along with its own dependencies (controller and models), will be downloaded by Tetra when the data-event action is invoked.
</p>
<p class="description">
    <b>data-comp="compName"</b> : To reduce HTTP requests, we can optionally associate the data-event with a packaged version of our dependency. Replace data-view with data-comp, providing a custom name compName for the packaged JavaScript.
</p>


&#60;div class="bootnode" data-view="likeApp/likeButton" data-event="click"&#62;<br>
...<br>
&#60;/div&#62;
<br>
&#60;div class="bootnode" data-comp="likePackage" data-event="click"&#62;<br>
...<br>
&#60;/div&#62;

<br><br>
<span class="subtitle">Dependency management system</span>

<p class="description">
    A view depends on one or more controllers, specified in its "use" parameter. Similarly, a controller depends on one or more models. When a bootnode event is invoked, Tetra downloads the view and its
    associated controllers and models. It then initializes each part of the application in the following order: models then controllers then view. Once finished, the data-event action is invoked.
</p>